# =====================================================================
# Netlify edge security headers.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# Helmet on the API protects /api/* responses; Netlify needs its own
# header pass for the static SPA bundle. The CSP here mirrors the one
# in `server/middleware/security.middleware.js` so the policy is
# uniform across both surfaces.
#
# `connect-src` MUST list every origin the SPA reaches over `fetch()`
# / `XHR`. That includes the Render API AND the Google Fonts hosts —
# the Workbox runtime cache (see `vite.config.js` -> `runtimeCaching`)
# revalidates `fonts.googleapis.com` (CSS) and `fonts.gstatic.com`
# (woff2) via `fetch()` from inside the Service Worker, so they are
# evaluated against `connect-src` rather than `style-src`/`font-src`.
# The Render URL also lives in the SPA's `VITE_API_BASE_URL`
# Netlify env var.
#
# `script-src` is locked to `'self'` with NO inline allowance. The
# theme/font-size bootstrap that used to be an inline <script> in
# `index.html` now lives in `public/theme-bootstrap.js`, so we never
# have to maintain a SHA-256 hash here. If you ever need to add a new
# inline block, prefer extracting it to /public/*.js over whitelisting
# a hash — every whitespace edit otherwise breaks CSP in production.
# =====================================================================

/*
  Content-Security-Policy: default-src 'self'; script-src 'self'; style-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' https://fonts.googleapis.com; font-src 'self' https://fonts.gstatic.com data:; img-src 'self' data: blob: https://res.cloudinary.com; media-src 'self' https://res.cloudinary.com; connect-src 'self' https://lms-mern-jby8.onrender.com https://fonts.googleapis.com https://fonts.gstatic.com; frame-src https://www.youtube.com https://www.youtube-nocookie.com https://player.vimeo.com https://player.cloudinary.com; object-src 'none'; base-uri 'self'; form-action 'self'; frame-ancestors 'none'; upgrade-insecure-requests
  Strict-Transport-Security: max-age=31536000; includeSubDomains; preload
  Referrer-Policy: strict-origin-when-cross-origin
  Permissions-Policy: camera=(), microphone=(), geolocation=(), interest-cohort=()
  X-Content-Type-Options: nosniff
  X-Frame-Options: DENY
  Cross-Origin-Opener-Policy: same-origin
  Cross-Origin-Resource-Policy: same-site

# Long-cache the hashed Vite assets — they are content-addressed so
# bumping the SPA build naturally invalidates them.
/assets/*
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=31536000, immutable

# =====================================================================
# Never cache the SPA shell or the Service Worker entry.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------
# `index.html` is the ONLY un-hashed bundle in the entire build — every
# script/style it references uses content-addressed filenames under
# `/assets/*`. If Netlify's edge (or the user's browser HTTP cache)
# serves an old `index.html`, two things break at the same time:
#   1. The CSP response header that travels with that HTML is the OLD
#      policy. The current API origin gets blocked under the previous
#      `connect-src` allow-list and every `/api/*` request fails — the
#      app paints an empty shell with no error UI.
#   2. The `<script>` tags inside that HTML point at chunk hashes that
#      were already deleted from `/assets/`, so React never mounts.
# Forcing `no-cache` here means the browser MUST revalidate `index.html`
# (and the SW entry that bootstraps it) on every navigation, which is
# what the `vite-plugin-pwa` auto-update flow assumes by design.
#
# Combined with `registrationOptions: { updateViaCache: 'none' }` in
# `vite.config.js`, this guarantees a fresh deploy reaches every
# returning visitor on their next pageload — no manual hard refresh,
# no "clear site data" support ticket.
# =====================================================================
/index.html
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate

/sw.js
  Cache-Control: public, max-age=0, must-revalidate
